@node Preface
@chapter Preface
@cindex preface
@cindex Bookmark-X and to Bookmark-X
@cindex fork of Bookmark-X

@dfn{Bookmark-X} is a fork of Drew Adams' Bookmark-X package, modernized
for GNU Emacs 30 and later. 
Bookmark-X supports the entire span of GNU Emacs from
version 20 through 26 — a quarter-century of Emacs history.  To run
on each release the source carried many conditional execution paths, many fallback
implementations of functions that became built-in years later,
runtime probes for keymaps and faces that were not always present,
and duplicated @code{defcustom} forms with different @code{:type}
widgets for each Emacs generation.  This fork simplifies it. It requires GNU
Emacs 30 or later and uses many of the modern built-ins that replaced coded functionality in Bookmark-X.

Upstream Bookmark-X shipped with two notable third-party integrations
that no longer match how most users work in Emacs 30: a deep tie-in to
Drew Adams' Icicles completion framework, and an active integration with
@code{emacs-w3m} (a popular external web browser in the mid-2000s).
This fork drops both.  In place of Icicles, Bookmark-X uses plain
@code{completing-read} everywhere and assumes the user brings their own
modern completion stack on top --- @code{vertico} and @code{consult}
with @code{marginalia} and @code{orderless}, or @code{helm}, or
@code{ivy}, all work without any package-specific glue (and
@code{consult-bookmark} adds live preview for free; @pxref{Live
Preview}).  In place of @code{emacs-w3m}, Bookmark-X uses the built-in
@code{eww} browser: legacy W3M bookmarks saved by older sessions are
still recognised by @code{bmkx-w3m-jump}, but their handler routes them
through @code{bmkx-jump-eww} so they keep working, and no new W3M
bookmarks are created.  This fork also adds an optional Casual Transient
menu.  @xref{Migration}, for the complete change list.

The goal of this fork is to retain the original functionality of
Bookmark-X.  The only major exception is that it does not replace the
bookmark package by replacing its functionality. Instead, it provides
functions that are equivalent to it.  For example, @code{bmkx-list} and
@code{bmkx-jump} instead of redefining @code{bookmark-list} and
@code{bookmark-jump}. This way, both packages can coexist.  In fact, 
built-in Bookmark can read bookmark files created by Bookmark-X and vice-versa.


@node Introduction
@chapter Introduction
@cindex introduction
@cindex Bookmark-X versus @file{bookmark.el}

Bookmark-X is a substantial extension of GNU Emacs's built-in
@file{bookmark.el}.  It keeps every concept from built-in
bookmarks---named, persistent placeholders into files, buffers, Info
nodes, and so on---but makes bookmarks useful as persistent records,
not just saved positions.

Bookmark-X enlarges built-in bookmarks in three directions:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Richer bookmarks.}  Bookmarks can carry tags, annotations,
region information, visit counts, last-access timestamps, and arbitrary
user data.  They can be highlighted in the buffer they point to, and
they remember where they were even when the file has been edited.

@item
@strong{More kinds of bookmarks.}  In addition to bookmarks that ``go''
to a location, Bookmark-X ships over 70 bookmark types: Dired buffers,
Info nodes, Gnus articles, EWW pages, @command{man} pages, image files,
URLs, desktops, keyboard macros, sets of variables, snippets of text,
sequences of other bookmarks, whole bookmark files, and more.

@item
@strong{More to do with bookmarks.}  The @file{*Bmkx List*} buffer is
significantly enhanced.  You can mark, sort, filter, omit, search,
query-replace, tag, retag, edit, clone, highlight, describe, and
copy/move bookmarks across multiple bookmark files.  You can save
bookmark-list views, define your own jump commands and sort orders, and
cycle through arbitrary sets of bookmarks (``the navigation list'').
@end enumerate

@cindex sibling design
@cindex relationship to @file{bookmark.el}
@strong{Bookmark-X is an additive sibling of the built-in
@file{bookmark.el}.}  Loading this package does @emph{not} redefine any
function from @file{bookmark.el}.  Every command in Bookmark-X lives
under the @code{bmkx-} prefix and is available from its own keymaps
(@kbd{C-x x}, @kbd{C-x j}, @kbd{C-x 4 j}).  The standard
@kbd{C-x r m}, @kbd{C-x r b} and @kbd{C-x r l} bindings still call the
built-in.  Both systems read and write the same on-disk bookmark file
format, so you can use either at any time.

If you would like the standard keys to invoke Bookmark-X instead, see
@ref{Standard Keys}.


@node Tutorial
@chapter Tutorial
@cindex tutorial
@cindex first session

This chapter walks through a typical first session.  Open a few files
you actually use, then follow along.

@section Creating Your First Bookmark
@cindex creating bookmarks, tutorial

Place point somewhere in a file you visit often---say, midway through
a long @file{README}.  Type:

@example
M-x bmkx-bookmark-set-confirm-overwrite RET
@end example

(The shorter key sequence is @kbd{C-x x m}.)  Emacs prompts for a
bookmark name; type @kbd{readme top RET}.  The bookmark is set at
point, and the bookmark file is updated on disk (if @code{bookmark-save-flag}
is @code{t}, which is the default).

@section Opening the Bookmark List
@cindex opening @file{*Bmkx List*}, tutorial

Type @kbd{C-x x e} (or @kbd{M-x bmkx-list}).  Buffer
@file{*Bmkx List*} appears.  You see one row per bookmark, in a marked,
sortable display.

Try the basics:

@table @kbd
@item n
Next line.
@item p
Previous line.
@item @key{RET}
Open the bookmark on the current line in the same window.
@item o
Open it in another window.
@item @key{TAB}
@itemx C-o
@emph{Preview} it in another window without leaving @file{*Bmkx List*}.
@item q
Quit.  The buffer is hidden; your bookmarks stay in memory.
@end table

@section Adding a Tag
@cindex tagging, tutorial

In @file{*Bmkx List*}, place point on the bookmark you just created.
Type @kbd{T +} (@code{bmkx-add-tags}).  At the @samp{Tag(s):} prompt
type @kbd{doc RET RET} (the empty entry ends the list).  A small
@samp{t} now appears on that bookmark's line, indicating it is tagged.

To list only tagged bookmarks: @kbd{T S}.  To show all again: @kbd{.}.

@section Jumping
@cindex jumping, tutorial

You can jump from anywhere in Emacs:

@example
C-x j j RET readme top RET
@end example

@code{bmkx-jump} prompts you with completion; type the bookmark name
or use your usual completion machinery to pick.  If the @code{consult}
package is loaded, you get live preview as you move through candidates.

To jump in the other window, use @kbd{C-x 4 j j}.  To jump only among
bookmarks of a specific type (Dired, Info, EWW, @dots{}), use
@kbd{C-x j :} and choose the type.

@section Filtering and Sorting
@cindex filtering, tutorial
@cindex sorting, tutorial

Open @file{*Bmkx List*} (@kbd{C-x x e}) and try:

@table @kbd
@item s s
Cycle through sort orders.  Repeat until something useful.
@item s n
Sort by bookmark name.
@item s d
Sort by last bookmark access (most recent first).
@item < @r{/} >
Show only unmarked / marked bookmarks.
@item P B
Incremental filter on bookmark name.  Type a regexp; press @key{RET} to
commit.
@item .
Show all bookmarks again.
@item M-t
Toggle the location column (file or buffer name).
@end table

@section Multiple Bookmarks at Once
@cindex marked bookmarks, tutorial

Mark several bookmarks with @kbd{m} (or @kbd{M-m} to mark all).  Then:

@table @kbd
@item T > +
Add tags to all marked bookmarks at once.
@item D
Delete all marked bookmarks (after confirmation).
@item M-d >
Open Dired on every local file among the marked bookmarks.
@item Y > +
Copy the marked bookmarks into another bookmark file.
@end table

@section Live Preview Mode
@cindex preview mode, tutorial

Type @kbd{M-p} in @file{*Bmkx List*}.  The mode-line lighter changes to
@samp{ Pv}.  Now moving point onto a row immediately opens that
bookmark's destination in another window---without selecting it.  Press
@kbd{M-p} again to turn the mode off; the window configuration is
restored to what it was when you entered the mode.

@section Saving and Switching Bookmark Files
@cindex bookmark files, tutorial

Your bookmarks live in @code{bookmark-default-file}
(@file{~/.emacs.d/bookmarks} by default), and are saved automatically.
To save explicitly: @kbd{S} in @file{*Bmkx List*}.  To switch to a
different bookmark file: @kbd{L} (@code{bmkx-switch-bookmark-file-create}).

That is the core workflow.  The rest of this manual reads as a
reference: each chapter covers one feature in detail.


@node Concepts
@chapter Concepts: list, file, display
@cindex concepts
@cindex bookmark list
@cindex bookmark file
@cindex bookmark-list display

Three different things are commonly confused.  Understanding them is
the single most important thing for using Bookmark-X effectively.

@table @asis
@item The bookmark list
The in-memory set of bookmarks.  It is the value of internal variable
@code{bookmark-alist}.  Adding, renaming, deleting, or jumping to a
bookmark updates this list.

@item The bookmark file
An on-disk persistent record of a set of bookmarks.  Its default
location is @code{bookmark-default-file}.  Multiple bookmark files may
exist; only one is @emph{current} at a time.

@item The bookmark-list display
Buffer @file{*Bmkx List*}.  It is a snapshot view of the bookmark list,
rendered with markings, sort order, filters, and so on.
@end table

These three can be out of sync.  The @emph{list} rules during an Emacs
session.  The @emph{file} rules across sessions (it is all that survives
when Emacs exits).  In the display,
@code{bmkx-bmenu-refresh-menu-list} (@kbd{g}) refreshes from the list;
with a prefix argument (@kbd{C-u g}) it reloads from the file.

