@node Prefix Keys
@section Prefix Keys
@cindex prefix keys
@cindex keymaps

Bookmark-X allocates dedicated prefix keys for bookmarking, separate
from the shared @kbd{C-x r} register prefix.

@multitable @columnfractions .35 .15 .50
@headitem Keymap @tab Default key @tab Purpose
@item @code{bookmark-map}              @tab @kbd{C-x x}    @tab General bookmark commands.
@item @code{bmkx-set-map}              @tab @kbd{C-x x c}  @tab Create (set) new bookmarks.
@item @code{bmkx-tags-map}             @tab @kbd{C-x x t}  @tab Tag commands.
@item @code{bmkx-annotate-map}         @tab @kbd{C-x x a}  @tab Annotation commands.
@item @code{bmkx-jump-map}             @tab @kbd{C-x j}    @tab Jump (visit) bookmarks (same window).
@item @code{bmkx-jump-other-window-map} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j} @tab Jump (other window).
@item built-in other-frame jump        @tab @kbd{C-x 5 j}  @tab Jump (other frame).
@end multitable

These prefixes are themselves customizable through three list-valued
options:

@vindex bmkx-bookmark-map-prefix-keys
@vindex bmkx-jump-map-prefix-keys
@vindex bmkx-jump-other-window-map-prefix-keys
@table @code
@item bmkx-bookmark-map-prefix-keys
Default @code{(list (kbd "C-x x"))}.
@item bmkx-jump-map-prefix-keys
Default @code{(list (kbd "C-x j"))}.
@item bmkx-jump-other-window-map-prefix-keys
Default @code{(list (kbd "C-x 4 j"))}.
@end table

Because they are lists, you can bind a keymap under several prefixes at
once.  The setter function rebinds the keys automatically when you
customize.


@node Standard Keys
@section Binding Bookmark-X to the Standard Keys
@cindex standard keys
@cindex @kbd{C-x r b}
@cindex @code{bookmark-jump} override

Loading Bookmark-X does not redefine any built-in command.  If you want
@kbd{C-x r m}, @kbd{C-x r b}, @kbd{C-x r l} to run the Bookmark-X
versions, add this to your init file:

@lisp
(define-key bookmark-map "m" #'bmkx-bookmark-set-confirm-overwrite)
(define-key bookmark-map "b" #'bmkx-jump)
(define-key bookmark-map "l" #'bmkx-list)
@end lisp

If you also want programmatic callers (@code{consult-bookmark},
@code{helm-bookmark}, Org-mode bookmark links, etc.) to pick up
Bookmark-X's enhancements when they invoke @code{bookmark-jump}, add:

@lisp
(advice-add 'bookmark-jump :override #'bmkx-jump)
@end lisp

No helper command is required.  These are plain Emacs primitives;
remove the lines (or call @code{advice-remove}) to reverse them.


@node Setting Bookmarks
@chapter Setting Bookmarks
@cindex setting bookmarks
@cindex creating bookmarks

@findex bmkx-bookmark-set-confirm-overwrite
@code{bmkx-bookmark-set-confirm-overwrite} (@kbd{C-x x m},
@kbd{C-x x c m}) is the enhanced replacement for @code{bookmark-set}:

@itemize
@item
Completion candidates default to bookmarks in the current buffer (or
all bookmarks if there are none), so you can easily update a nearby
bookmark.  A numeric prefix argument expands completion to all
bookmarks.
@item
Overwriting prompts for confirmation.
@item
Existing tags and annotations are preserved when you re-set a bookmark
(see @code{bmkx-properties-to-keep}).
@end itemize

@section Type-Specific Creation Commands
@cindex creation commands by type

The @code{bmkx-set-map} (default prefix @kbd{C-x x c}) groups commands
that create specific kinds of bookmark:

@multitable @columnfractions .42 .18 .40
@headitem Command @tab Key @tab Creates
@item @code{bmkx-bookmark-set-confirm-overwrite}  @tab @kbd{C-x x c m} @tab A normal bookmark at point.
@item @code{bmkx-autofile-set}                    @tab @kbd{C-x x c a} @tab An autofile bookmark for a file.
@item @code{bmkx-file-target-set}                 @tab @kbd{C-x x c f} @tab A file bookmark (file name at point).
@item @code{bmkx-url-target-set}                  @tab @kbd{C-x x c u} @tab A URL bookmark.
@item @code{bmkx-make-function-bookmark}          @tab @kbd{C-x x c F} @tab A function or last-kbd-macro bookmark.
@item @code{bmkx-set-desktop-bookmark}            @tab @kbd{C-x x c K} @tab A desktop bookmark.
@item @code{bmkx-set-sequence-bookmark}           @tab @kbd{C-x x c s} @tab A composite bookmark.
@item @code{bmkx-set-bookmark-file-bookmark}      @tab @kbd{C-x x c y} @tab A bookmark-file bookmark.
@item @code{bmkx-set-snippet-bookmark}            @tab @kbd{C-x x M-w} @tab A snippet bookmark from the region.
@item @code{bmkx-wrap-bookmark-with-last-kbd-macro} @tab @kbd{C-x x c C-k} @tab A sequence: a bookmark + the last kbd macro.
@item @code{bmkx-toggle-autonamed-bookmark-set/delete} @tab @kbd{C-x x c @key{RET}} @tab Set or delete the autonamed bookmark here.
@end multitable

@section Bookmarking Without Visiting
@cindex bookmarking without visiting

You can bookmark targets without first opening them:

@itemize
@item
@strong{A file or URL at point.}  @code{bmkx-file-target-set}
(@kbd{C-x x c f}) and @code{bmkx-url-target-set} (@kbd{C-x x c u}) read
a file or URL with the text at point as the default.
@item
@strong{Compilation, grep, occur hits.}  In @file{*compilation*},
@file{*grep*}, @file{*Occur*}, and @file{*Multi-Occur*} buffers,
@code{bmkx-compilation-target-set} or @code{bmkx-occur-target-set}
(@kbd{C-c C-b}) bookmarks the target of the hit at point.  The
@kbd{C-c C-M-b} variant bookmarks every hit;
@code{bmkx-occur-create-autonamed-bookmarks} (@kbd{C-c C-M-B} in Occur)
creates an autonamed bookmark per hit.
@item
@strong{Marked files in Dired} (requires @file{dired+.el}).
@code{diredp-do-bookmark} (@kbd{M-b}) bookmarks each marked file as an
autofile.
@end itemize


@node Jumping
@chapter Jumping to Bookmarks
@cindex jumping
@cindex visiting bookmarks

@findex bmkx-jump
@findex bmkx-jump-other-window
@code{bmkx-jump} (@kbd{C-x j j}) is the generic bookmark jump command;
completion offers every bookmark.  @code{bmkx-jump-other-window}
(@kbd{C-x 4 j j}) is its other-window twin.  Inside @file{*Bmkx List*},
@key{RET} or @kbd{f} calls @code{bmkx-list-this-window}, and @kbd{o}
calls @code{bmkx-list-other-window}.

@section Type-Specific Jump Commands
@cindex type-specific jump

Each bookmark type has its own jump command that offers only bookmarks
of that type as completion candidates.  They live on
@code{bmkx-jump-map} (default @kbd{C-x j}) and
@code{bmkx-jump-other-window-map} (default @kbd{C-x 4 j}).  A small
sampler:

@multitable @columnfractions .30 .28 .42
@headitem Type @tab Same-window @tab Other-window
@item File           @tab @kbd{C-x j f} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j f}
@item Local file     @tab @kbd{C-x j l} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j l}
@item Remote file    @tab @kbd{C-x j n} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j n}
@item Autofile       @tab @kbd{C-x j a} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j a}
@item Non-file       @tab @kbd{C-x j b} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j b}
@item Dired          @tab @kbd{C-x j d} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j d}
@item Info           @tab @kbd{C-x j i} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j i}
@item @command{man}  @tab @kbd{C-x j m} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j m}
@item EWW            @tab @kbd{C-x j e} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j e}
@item Gnus           @tab @kbd{C-x j g} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j g}
@item Image          @tab @kbd{C-x j M-i} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j M-i}
@item Region         @tab @kbd{C-x j r} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j r}
@item URL            @tab @kbd{C-x j u} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j u}
@item Highlighted    @tab @kbd{C-x j h} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j h}
@item Snippet        @tab @kbd{C-x j M-w} @tab @kbd{C-x 4 j M-w}
@end multitable

The generic ``any type'' command is @code{bmkx-jump-to-type}
(@kbd{C-x j :}).  It first asks for the type, then offers only
bookmarks of that type.  Useful when you do not want to remember the
type-specific keys.

@section @code{find-file}-Style Jumping
@cindex @code{find-file}-style jumping

@findex bmkx-find-file
@code{bmkx-find-file} (@kbd{C-x j C-f}) acts like @code{find-file}, but
obeys @code{bmkx-default-handlers-for-file-types}---so HTML files open
in @code{browse-url}, Word docs in @code{w32-browser}, and so on.  With
a prefix argument it also creates an autofile bookmark for the file.

There is a family of @code{bmkx-find-file-...-tags} commands (under
@kbd{C-x j t C-f ...}) that filter by tags while reading a file name
with @code{read-file-name}, so you can browse directories.

@section Mode-Specific @kbd{j}
@cindex mode-specific @kbd{j} bindings

Several modes bind @kbd{j} to the corresponding type-specific jump:

@multitable @columnfractions .35 .65
@headitem Mode @tab @kbd{j} jumps to a@dots{}
@item Info             @tab Info bookmark.
@item Gnus summary     @tab Gnus bookmark.
@item @command{man} / @command{woman} @tab @command{man}-page bookmark.
@item EWW              @tab EWW bookmark.
@item Buffer-menu      @tab Non-file bookmark.
@item Dired (@kbd{C-j}) @tab Dired bookmark whose directory is the current one.
@end multitable

@section Tag-Based Jumping
@cindex tag-based jumping

Tag-aware jump commands combine three ideas: which bookmark family
(file, autofile, this-dir-file, find-file), how many tags must match
(all = @kbd{*}, some = @kbd{+}), and whether matching is literal or
against a regexp (@kbd{%}).

@multitable @columnfractions .42 .22 .36
@headitem Command @tab Key @tab Meaning
@item @code{bmkx-all-tags-jump}             @tab @kbd{C-x j t *}     @tab With all given tags.
@item @code{bmkx-some-tags-jump}            @tab @kbd{C-x j t +}     @tab With at least one tag.
@item @code{bmkx-all-tags-regexp-jump}      @tab @kbd{C-x j t % *}   @tab Every tag matches a regexp.
@item @code{bmkx-some-tags-regexp-jump}     @tab @kbd{C-x j t % +}   @tab Some tag matches a regexp.
@item @code{bmkx-file-all-tags-jump}        @tab @kbd{C-x j t f *}   @tab File bookmark with all tags.
@item @code{bmkx-find-file-all-tags}        @tab @kbd{C-x j t C-f *} @tab @code{read-file-name} version.
@end multitable

Each command has an @code{-other-window} twin under
@kbd{C-x 4 j t ...}.


@node The Bmkx List Buffer
@chapter The @file{*Bmkx List*} Buffer
@cindex @file{*Bmkx List*}
@cindex bmkx-list-mode
@cindex bookmark browse buffer

Open it with @code{bmkx-list} (@kbd{C-x x e}).  This buffer is the
heart of the interactive workflow: filtering, marking, sorting,
tagging, highlighting, editing---everything happens here.

Major mode: @code{bmkx-list-mode}, derived from @code{special-mode}.

@section Header and Mark Columns
@cindex header line
@cindex marks
@cindex flags

The header shows the current bookmark file and a @dfn{title}
describing the current filter (e.g.@: @samp{File and Directory
Bookmarks} or @samp{All Bookmarks}).  The mode line shows counts:
marked (@kbd{>}), flagged for deletion (@kbd{D}), tagged (@kbd{t}),
temporary (@kbd{X}), annotated (@kbd{a}), modified-unsaved (@kbd{*}),
plus the sort order.  When a counter is split, @samp{N/M} means ``N up
to and including the current line, of M total.''

Per-line flags:

@multitable @columnfractions .15 .85
@headitem Mark @tab Meaning
@item @kbd{>}   @tab Marked.
@item @kbd{D}   @tab Flagged for deletion.
@item @kbd{a}   @tab Has an annotation.
@item @kbd{t}   @tab Has at least one tag.
@item @kbd{X}   @tab Temporary---will not be saved.
@item @kbd{*}   @tab Modified since the last save of the bookmark file.
@end multitable

@section Filename Display Style
@cindex filename style
@cindex shrinking paths
@cindex @code{bmkx-bmenu-filename-style}

Long file paths often get truncated at the right edge of the window,
hiding the basename---which is usually the most informative part of
the path.  The option @code{bmkx-bmenu-filename-style} controls how
the recorded path is reformatted before display.  It does not change
the bookmark data; only the on-screen rendering.

@multitable @columnfractions .18 .82
@headitem Value @tab Example
@item @code{full}       @tab @file{/Users/dmg/.emacs.d/modules/bookmark-x/bookmark-x-1.el}
@item @code{abbreviate} @tab @file{~/.emacs.d/modules/bookmark-x/bookmark-x-1.el}
@item @code{shrink}     @tab @file{~/.e/m/b/bookmark-x-1.el}
@item @code{basename}   @tab @file{bookmark-x-1.el}
@end multitable

The default is @code{abbreviate}.  The @code{shrink} style collapses
each parent directory to its first character (two characters when the
directory name starts with a dot, so @samp{.emacs.d} becomes
@samp{.e} and not just @samp{.}) and always preserves the basename
intact.

Only paths that look like absolute filenames are reformatted.  Buffer
names, @code{location} strings, and other non-path locations pass
through unchanged.

@table @kbd
@item M-F
@code{bmkx-bmenu-cycle-filename-style}---cycle the option through
@code{full} @result{} @code{abbreviate} @result{} @code{shrink}
@result{} @code{basename} and re-render the buffer in place.
@end table

You can also set the option directly with
@code{bmkx-bmenu-set-filename-style} (which prompts with completion),
or through the Customize interface.  The Casual menu (@pxref{Casual
Integration}) exposes the same cycle entry as @kbd{M-F}, with a label
that displays the current value.

@section Tags Column
@cindex tags column
@cindex @code{bmkx-bmenu-show-tags-flag}
@cindex @code{bmkx-bmenu-tags-column-width}
@cindex @code{bmkx-bmenu-name-column-width}

By default, the bookmark list shows a single @samp{t} flag for tagged
bookmarks but no indication of @emph{which} tags they have.  Enable
@code{bmkx-bmenu-show-tags-flag} to add a dedicated tags column
between the bookmark name and the file/location column.  The @samp{t}
flag is preserved.

@multitable @columnfractions .35 .65
@headitem Option @tab Effect
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-show-tags-flag} @tab
Master switch.  When non-nil, the tags column is rendered.  Default
@code{t}.  Set to @code{nil} to restore the historical layout
(name column followed immediately by the file/location column).
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-tags-column-width} @tab
Width of the tags column in characters.  Default @code{18}.  Joined
tag names exceeding this width are truncated with @samp{@dots{}}; if
shorter, padded with spaces.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-name-column-width} @tab
Maximum width of the bookmark-name column.  @code{nil} (default) uses
the longest current name.  An integer truncates longer names with
@samp{@dots{}}, useful for keeping layout stable when names vary in
length.
@end multitable

Tags are joined with a comma and no space, to maximise information
density.  A bookmark tagged @samp{alpha}, @samp{beta}, @samp{gamma}
in an 18-char column renders as @samp{alpha,beta,gamma  }; in a
12-char column it renders as @samp{alpha,beta,@dots{}}.

@table @kbd
@item M-T
@code{bmkx-bmenu-toggle-tags-column}---flip the master switch and
redisplay.  Reports the new state in the echo area.
@end table

To change widths interactively, use @code{bmkx-bmenu-set-tags-column-width}
and @code{bmkx-bmenu-set-name-column-width} (both prompt for an
integer; pass @code{0} to the name-width command for @samp{auto}).
The Casual menu's Tags submenu exposes the toggle and both width
commands.

When the tags column is on (or @code{bmkx-bmenu-name-column-width} is
set), @code{bookmark-bmenu-file-column} is automatically raised in the
buffer so file paths do not overlap the new columns.  Your custom
value, if larger, is preserved.

