@section Defining Commands From the View
@cindex defining commands from view

@table @kbd
@item C-c C-c
@code{bmkx-bmenu-define-command}---define a command that restores the
current display state (sort/filter/etc.).
@item C-c C-S-c
@code{bmkx-bmenu-define-full-snapshot-command}---restores the full
bookmark list including marks.  Larger but complete.
@item C-c C-j
@code{bmkx-bmenu-define-jump-marked-command}---a type-specific jump
command whose candidates are the marked bookmarks.
@end table

Defined commands are appended to @code{bmkx-bmenu-commands-file},
which is loaded automatically on first opening @file{*Bmkx List*}.

@section Preview Mode
@cindex preview mode, in @file{*Bmkx List*}

@kbd{M-p} (@code{bmkx-list-preview-mode}) toggles live preview of the
bookmark on point.  @xref{Live Preview}, for details.

@section Casual Menu
@cindex Casual menu, in @file{*Bmkx List*}

@kbd{c} (@code{casual-bmkx-tmenu}) opens a Transient-based menu UI if
the @code{casual-lib} package is installed.  @xref{Casual Integration}.

@section Controlling Where the List Opens
@cindex window placement, of @file{*Bmkx List*}
@cindex @code{display-buffer-alist}, for @file{*Bmkx List*}

When called interactively, @code{bmkx-list} hands the buffer to
@code{pop-to-buffer-same-window}: by default the list replaces the
buffer in the currently-selected window.  No frames or windows are
created, deleted, or resized -- Emacs's normal display rules apply.

To override the default placement, add an entry for the buffer name
@file{*Bmkx List*} to @code{display-buffer-alist}; that variable
takes precedence over the package's default.  A few useful recipes:

@example
;; Always in the current window (this is the default; included for
;; completeness):
(add-to-list 'display-buffer-alist
             '("\\*Bmkx List\\*" (display-buffer-same-window)))

;; Dedicated side window on the right, 60 columns wide:
(add-to-list 'display-buffer-alist
             '("\\*Bmkx List\\*"
               (display-buffer-in-side-window)
               (side . right) (window-width . 60)))

;; A dedicated frame named "Bookmarks":
(add-to-list 'display-buffer-alist
             '("\\*Bmkx List\\*"
               (display-buffer-pop-up-frame)
               (pop-up-frame-parameters
                (name . "Bookmarks") (width . 100) (height . 40))))

;; Re-use whichever window most recently showed the list, otherwise
;; pop a new window below the current one:
(add-to-list 'display-buffer-alist
             '("\\*Bmkx List\\*"
               (display-buffer-reuse-window display-buffer-below-selected)))
@end example

The same recipes apply to the @file{*Bmkx Preview*} buffer used by
live preview mode (@pxref{Live Preview}).


@node Bookmark Types
@chapter Bookmark Types
@cindex bookmark types
@cindex types of bookmark

A bookmark @dfn{type} is really just a @dfn{handler}: a function that
``jumps to'' (acts on) the bookmark.  Bookmark-X ships handlers for
around 70 of them.

Run @kbd{M-x bmkx-types-alist} to list every type registered in your
session.  @code{bmkx-jump-to-type} (@kbd{C-x j :}) lets you pick a type
interactively.  Predicates of the form @code{bmkx-TYPE-bookmark-p}
recognize each type.

@section Location / File Bookmarks

@itemize
@item @strong{File / local file / remote file.}  Jumping visits the file.
@item @strong{Directory.}  Like a file bookmark, but the destination is
a directory.
@item @strong{Non-file (buffer).}  Like a file bookmark for a buffer
that is not visiting a file.
@item @strong{Region.}  A bookmark with @code{front-context-string},
@code{rear-context-string}, plus an @code{end-position} property.
Jumping activates the region (controlled by @code{bmkx-use-region}).
@code{bmkx-region-jump-narrow-indirect-other-window} (@kbd{C-x 4 j R})
narrows the region into a cloned indirect buffer.
@end itemize

@section Autofile Bookmarks
@cindex autofile

An @dfn{autofile} is a bookmark whose name is the non-directory part of
its file name.  @code{bmkx-autofile-set} (@kbd{C-x x c a}) creates one.
Combined with tags this gives you a filesystem-wide metadata layer.
Related options: @code{bmkx-autofile-filecache} (advise
@code{file-cache-add-file} to also create autofiles),
@code{bmkx-autofile-access-invokes-bookmark-flag} (make @code{find-file}
also ``visit'' the autofile, updating its visit count).

@section Dired and Dired-Tree Bookmarks
@cindex Dired bookmarks

A Dired bookmark records:

@itemize
@item the Dired directory,
@item the @command{ls} switches,
@item which files are marked,
@item which subdirectories are inserted,
@item which subdirectories are hidden.
@end itemize

Jumping reproduces the Dired buffer with the same markings, inserted
subdirs, and hidden subdirs.  A @dfn{Dired-tree bookmark} is a sequence
bookmark whose components are Dired bookmarks for a directory and its
descendants.  @code{diredp-do-bookmark-dirs-recursive} (from
@file{dired+.el}) creates one for the current Dired buffer.

@section Info, @command{man}, EWW, Gnus

@itemize
@item @strong{Info.}  @code{bmkx-info-jump} (@kbd{C-x j i}, or @kbd{j}
in Info mode).  Mode @code{bmkx-info-auto-bookmark-mode} automatically
creates or updates an Info bookmark every time you visit a node.
@item @strong{@command{man} / @command{woman}.}  @code{bmkx-man-jump}
(@kbd{C-x j m}).
@item @strong{EWW.}  @code{bmkx-eww-jump} (@kbd{C-x j e}).  EWW can be
configured so that visiting a page records a bookmark, via
@code{bmkx-eww-replace-keys-flag} which rebinds the built-in EWW
bookmark keys to Bookmark-X's.
@item @strong{Gnus.}  @code{bmkx-gnus-jump} bookmarks a Gnus article
(group, article, message-id).
@item @strong{Legacy W3M.}  @code{bmkx-w3m-jump} still recognises legacy
W3M bookmarks saved by earlier versions of Bookmark-X, but opens them in
EWW.  This fork does not create new W3M bookmarks.
@end itemize

@section Image Bookmarks
@cindex image bookmarks

When you bookmark an image-file target, Emacs's image handler is used
automatically.  @code{bmkx-image-jump} (@kbd{C-x j M-i}) jumps to one;
the description (@kbd{C-h @key{RET}}) shows the full EXIF metadata
(requires @command{exiftool}).

@section URL Bookmarks

@code{bmkx-url-target-set} (@kbd{C-x x c u}) and @code{bmkx-url-jump}
(@kbd{C-x j u}).  The handler is typically @code{browse-url}.

@section Desktop Bookmarks
@cindex desktop bookmarks

@code{bmkx-set-desktop-bookmark} (@kbd{C-x x K}) captures a desktop
(from @file{desktop.el}).  Jumping restores the saved desktop.

Options:
@itemize
@item @code{bmkx-desktop-no-save-vars}---variables to exclude.
@item @code{bmkx-desktop-jump-save-before-flag}---save current desktop
before jumping if it was reached by jumping.
@item @code{bmkx-desktop-save-as-last}---add to @code{kill-emacs-hook}
to remember the last jumped-to desktop.
@end itemize

@section Sequence (Composite) Bookmarks
@cindex sequence bookmarks
@cindex composite bookmarks

A @dfn{sequence bookmark} invokes each member bookmark in turn.
@code{bmkx-set-sequence-bookmark} (@kbd{C-x x c s}) prompts for a
sequence name and the member bookmark names.
@code{bmkx-bmenu-make-sequence-from-marked} turns the marked bookmarks
into a sequence in their current order.  Members may themselves be
sequence bookmarks.

@section Function and Keyboard-Macro Bookmarks

@code{bmkx-make-function-bookmark} (@kbd{C-x x c F}) records a function
symbol or a lambda expression.  With a prefix argument it captures
@code{last-kbd-macro}---a persistent way to replay a keyboard macro.
@code{bmkx-wrap-bookmark-with-last-kbd-macro} (@kbd{C-x x c C-k})
builds a sequence bookmark that first invokes another bookmark and
then plays the macro.

@section Variable-List Bookmarks

@code{bmkx-set-variable-list-bookmark} records a set of variables and
their current values.  @code{bmkx-jump-variable-list} (@kbd{C-x j v})
restores them in the bookmark's buffer.

@section Snippet Bookmarks
@cindex snippet bookmarks

@code{bmkx-set-snippet-bookmark} (@kbd{C-x x M-w}) saves the active
region's text under a bookmark name.  At any time, in any Emacs
session, @code{bmkx-snippet-to-kill-ring} (@kbd{C-x j M-w}) yanks the
saved snippet to the kill ring.

@section Bookmark-List Bookmarks
@cindex bookmark-list bookmarks

A @dfn{bookmark-list bookmark} records the state of @file{*Bmkx List*}
(sort order, filter, regexp pattern, title, omit list).  Jumping to it
restores that state.  Defined as either a real bookmark or as a
command via @kbd{C-c C-c} (@code{bmkx-bmenu-define-command}).

@section Bookmark-File Bookmarks
@cindex bookmark-file bookmarks

Created by @code{bmkx-set-bookmark-file-bookmark} (@kbd{C-x x c y}).
``Jumping'' to one @emph{loads} the referenced bookmark file.  With
@kbd{C-u}, jumping @emph{switches} to it.

@section Defining Your Own Types

Define a handler function and set @code{bookmark-make-record-function}
(or pass a handler via your own bookmark setter).  To register a new
type so @code{bmkx-jump-to-type} recognizes it, provide a function
@code{bmkx-TYPE-alist-only} and call
@code{(bmkx-define-history-variables)}.  The macro
@code{bmkx-define-type-from-handler} (in @file{bookmark-x-mac.el}) does
all of this and also generates a predicate @code{bmkx-TYPE-bookmark-p}
and a ``show only'' command @code{bmkx-bmenu-show-only-TYPE-bookmarks}.


@node Tags
@chapter Tags
@cindex tags

A bookmark @dfn{tag} is a string (or a string plus a Lisp value)
attached to a bookmark.  Tags are persistent.  Multiple bookmarks can
share the same tag; one bookmark can have many.  Tags define @emph{sets}
of bookmarks (@samp{blue}, @samp{vacation/2024/photos}, @samp{todo},
@dots{}) and most Bookmark-X commands can operate on those sets.

@section Adding and Removing Tags

@multitable @columnfractions .42 .22 .14 .22
@headitem Command @tab Global key @tab Bmenu key @tab Action
@item @code{bmkx-add-tags} / @code{bmkx-bmenu-add-tags}       @tab @kbd{C-x x t + b} @tab @kbd{T +} @tab Add tags.
@item @code{bmkx-remove-tags} / @code{bmkx-bmenu-remove-tags} @tab @kbd{C-x x t - b} @tab @kbd{T -} @tab Remove tags.
@item @code{bmkx-remove-all-tags} / @code{bmkx-bmenu-remove-all-tags} @tab @kbd{C-x x t 0} @tab @kbd{T 0} @tab Remove all tags.
@item @code{bmkx-autofile-add-tags}     @tab @kbd{C-x x t + a} @tab (none)   @tab Tag a file (creates autofile).
@item @code{bmkx-untag-a-file}          @tab @kbd{C-x x t - a} @tab (none)   @tab Untag a file.
@item @code{bmkx-copy-tags}             @tab @kbd{C-x x t c}   @tab @kbd{T c} @tab Copy tags to a kill-ring-style slot.
@item @code{bmkx-paste-add-tags}        @tab @kbd{C-x x t p}   @tab @kbd{T p} @tab Paste (additive).
@item @code{bmkx-paste-replace-tags}    @tab @kbd{C-x x t q}   @tab @kbd{T q} @tab Paste (replace).
@item @code{bmkx-rename-tag}            @tab @kbd{C-x x t r}   @tab @kbd{T r} @tab Rename a tag everywhere.
@item @code{bmkx-edit-tags}             @tab @kbd{C-x x t e}   @tab @kbd{T e} @tab Edit a bookmark's tags.
@item @code{bmkx-list-all-tags}         @tab @kbd{C-x x t l}   @tab @kbd{T l} @tab List every defined tag.
@item @code{bmkx-set-tag-value}         @tab @kbd{C-x x t v}   @tab @kbd{T v} @tab Give a tag a value.
@end multitable

The tag prompt uses @code{completing-read-multiple}: enter tags in a
single, comma-separated reply (@samp{work,urgent,backend}).  Each
segment between commas has its own completion against the candidate
list.  Press @key{RET} on an empty input to accept the empty set
(many commands treat that as ``any tag at all'').  Use @kbd{C-q C-j}
to include a newline in a tag.

Inside @file{*Bmkx List*}, @kbd{T +}, @kbd{T -}, @kbd{T 0}, @kbd{T v}
and the Casual tags menu act on the bookmark on the current line --
no separate bookmark prompt.  Outside the list, the @code{bmkx-*}
variants prompt for the bookmark first.

@section Marking by Tag in @file{*Bmkx List*}

The tag-based mark and unmark commands live under @kbd{T m} / @kbd{T u}:

@multitable @columnfractions .47 .15 .38
@headitem Command @tab Key @tab Marks/unmarks bookmarks tagged...
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-mark-bookmarks-tagged-all}     @tab @kbd{T m *}   @tab with all of the given tags.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-mark-bookmarks-tagged-some}    @tab @kbd{T m +}   @tab with some of them.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-mark-bookmarks-tagged-not-all} @tab @kbd{T m ~ *} @tab not with all of them.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-mark-bookmarks-tagged-none}    @tab @kbd{T m ~ +} @tab with none of them.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-mark-bookmarks-tagged-regexp}  @tab @kbd{T m %}   @tab with a tag matching a regexp.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-show-only-tagged-bookmarks}    @tab @kbd{T S}     @tab show only tagged.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-show-only-untagged-bookmarks}  @tab @kbd{T U}     @tab show only untagged.
@end multitable

A prefix argument flips ``some'' / ``not all'' and ``all'' / ``none.''

@section Tag Values
@cindex tag values

Use @code{bmkx-set-tag-value} (@kbd{T v} in @file{*Bmkx List*}) to give
a tag any readable Lisp value: number, string, list, etc.  A tag with
a value is internally @code{(NAME . VALUE)}.  Most Bookmark-X commands
ignore values; you can use them from your own Lisp.

A single predefined tag has special behaviour: @code{bmkx-jump}.  If
its value is a function, that function is called just after
@code{bookmark-after-jump-hook} runs for the tagged bookmark.

Tag names prefixed with @code{bmkx-} are reserved.

@section Pseudo-Hierarchical Tags
@cindex hierarchical tags

A simple convention---tag names that look like paths
(@samp{vacation/2024/winter/photos})---gives you a tree-shaped
organization without any special syntax.  Use completion (@key{TAB})
on partial prefixes to descend the ``tree.''


@node Annotations
@chapter Annotations
@cindex annotations

An annotation is free-text metadata attached to a bookmark.

@table @code
@item bmkx-annotate-bookmark
@kbd{C-x x a a}.  Prompts for a bookmark and opens an annotation edit buffer.
@item bookmark-show-annotation
@kbd{C-x x a s}.  Shows an annotation in read-only mode (@kbd{C-x C-q}
toggles to edit mode).
@item bookmark-show-all-annotations
@kbd{C-x x a S}.
@item bmkx-annotate-bookmark-this-file/buffer
@kbd{C-x x a b}.
@item bmkx-annotate-all-bookmarks-this-file/buffer
@kbd{C-x x a B}.
@end table

In the edit buffer:

@itemize
@item @code{bookmark-send-edited-annotation} saves (@kbd{C-c C-c}; or
@kbd{C-c C-M-c} when Org mode owns @kbd{C-c C-c}).
@item @code{bookmark-kill-annotation} (@kbd{C-x C-k}) discards changes.
@item The buffer's major mode is controlled by
@code{bmkx-annotation-modes-inherit-from} (default @code{org-mode}).
@item @code{bookmark-automatically-show-annotations}---if non-nil,
jumping to a bookmark pops up its annotation.
@end itemize

@section External Annotations (``Annotation Forwards'')

Keep the inline annotation short and ``forward'' to a file, URL, or
another bookmark.  Put one of these as the first non-blank line:

@example
bmkx-annot-url: "FILE"      ; opens with find-file-other-window
bmkx-annot-url: "URL"       ; opens with browse-url
bmkx-annot-url: "BOOKMARK"  ; jumps to the named bookmark
@end example

When you @emph{show} the annotation, Bookmark-X follows the forward.
When you @emph{edit} it (@kbd{a e}), you still see the literal text.

@section Annotation Commands in @file{*Bmkx List*}

@multitable @columnfractions .47 .15 .38
@headitem Command @tab Key @tab Meaning
@item @code{bmkx-list-show-annotation}                @tab @kbd{a a}     @tab Show this line's annotation.
@item @code{bmkx-edit-annotation}                     @tab @kbd{a e}     @tab Edit this line's annotation.
@item @code{bmkx-show-all-annotations}                @tab @kbd{a A}     @tab Show all annotations.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-edit-annotations-for-marked}   @tab @kbd{a >}     @tab Edit annotations for marked.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-show-this-annotation+move-down} @tab @kbd{M-@key{down}} @tab Move + show.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-show-this-annotation+move-up}   @tab @kbd{M-@key{up}}   @tab Same, going up.
@end multitable

Annotated bookmarks are flagged with @kbd{a} in the display.


@node Multiple Bookmark Files
@chapter Multiple Bookmark Files
@cindex multiple bookmark files

A bookmark file is a physical file on disk containing complete bookmark
records.  Bookmark-X makes it easy to:

@itemize
@item Switch to a different bookmark file (replacing the current
in-memory set).
@item Accumulate bookmarks by loading additional files.
@item Save the current bookmarks to a different file with
@code{bookmark-write} (@kbd{C-x x w}).
@item Create an empty bookmark file with @code{bmkx-empty-file}
(@kbd{C-x x 0}).
@end itemize

@section Switching

@multitable @columnfractions .47 .18 .35
@headitem Command @tab Key @tab Meaning
@item @code{bmkx-switch-bookmark-file-create}  @tab @kbd{C-x x L} or @kbd{L} @tab Switch to another bookmark file.
@item @code{bmkx-load} (no prefix)             @tab @kbd{C-x x l} or @kbd{l} @tab Add bookmarks from a file.
@item @code{bmkx-load} (with prefix)           @tab @kbd{C-u C-x x l} @tab Equivalent to @kbd{L} (switch).
@item @code{bmkx-switch-to-bookmark-file-this-file/buffer} @tab @kbd{C-x x C-l} @tab Switch to a file with only this buffer's bookmarks.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-load-marked-bookmark-file-bookmarks} @tab @kbd{M-l} @tab Load every marked bookmark-file bookmark.
@end multitable

@section Copying / Moving / Creating

@multitable @columnfractions .47 .15 .38
@headitem Command @tab Key @tab Meaning
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-copy-marked-to-bookmark-file}     @tab @kbd{Y > +} @tab Copy marked to another bookmark file.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-move-marked-to-bookmark-file}     @tab @kbd{Y > -} @tab Move them.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-create-bookmark-file-from-marked} @tab @kbd{Y > 0} @tab New file from marked.
@end multitable

@section Bookmark-File Bookmarks
@cindex bookmark-file bookmarks

Created with @code{bmkx-set-bookmark-file-bookmark} (@kbd{C-x x c y}).
``Jumping'' to one @emph{loads} that bookmark file; with @kbd{C-u} it
@emph{switches} to it.

@section Default for the Next Session
@vindex bmkx-last-as-first-bookmark-file

The default bookmark file for the next Emacs session is the one in use
when you quit, controlled by @code{bmkx-last-as-first-bookmark-file}.
Set this to @code{nil} to always start from @code{bookmark-default-file}.

Bookmark files are @emph{physical}, not logical, groupings.  Copying a
bookmark from one to another duplicates it; the two copies are
independent thereafter.


@node Highlighting
@chapter Highlighting Bookmark Locations
@cindex highlighting bookmarks

Optional---requires @file{bookmark-x-lit.el} on your @code{load-path}.
Bookmark-X can draw a persistent @dfn{highlight} at the position (or
region, or line, or fringe) of a bookmark in its buffer.

@section Styles

@multitable @columnfractions .30 .70
@headitem Style @tab Effect
@item @code{region}                 @tab Highlight the recorded region.
@item @code{line}                   @tab Highlight the bookmark's line.
@item @code{point}                  @tab Highlight the character at the bookmark position.
@item @code{line-beginning}         @tab Highlight the first character on the line.
@item @code{lfringe}                @tab Bitmap in the left fringe.
@item @code{line+lfringe}           @tab Both.
@item @code{rfringe}                @tab Bitmap in the right fringe.
@item @code{line+rfringe}           @tab Both.
@end multitable

Default style per kind (option):

@multitable @columnfractions .50 .50
@item @code{bmkx-light-style-autonamed}             @tab @code{line+lfringe}
@item @code{bmkx-light-style-non-autonamed}         @tab @code{line+rfringe}
@item @code{bmkx-light-style-autonamed-region}      @tab @code{region}
@item @code{bmkx-light-style-non-autonamed-region}  @tab @code{region}
@end multitable

@section Per-Bookmark Overrides (in @file{*Bmkx List*})

@multitable @columnfractions .47 .15 .38
@headitem Command @tab Key @tab Meaning
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-set-lighting}              @tab @kbd{H +}   @tab Set highlighting for this bookmark.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-set-lighting-for-marked}   @tab @kbd{H > +} @tab For all marked.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-light}                     @tab @kbd{H H}   @tab Highlight this bookmark.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-light-marked}              @tab @kbd{H > H} @tab All marked.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-unlight}                   @tab @kbd{H U}   @tab Unhighlight this bookmark.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-unlight-marked}            @tab @kbd{H > U} @tab All marked.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-mark-lighted-bookmarks}    @tab @kbd{H M}   @tab Mark highlighted bookmarks.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-show-only-lighted-bookmarks} @tab @kbd{H S} @tab Show only highlighted.
@end multitable

Each setter command prompts for a style and face, and for a
@emph{condition}---an Emacs-Lisp sexp evaluated whenever the bookmark
is about to be highlighted.  Returning @code{:no-light} suppresses the
highlight.  The sexp may refer to free variables @code{this-bookmark}
and @code{this-bookmark-name}.

@section Automatic Highlighting

@itemize
@item @code{bmkx-auto-light-when-set}---highlight automatically when a
bookmark is created.
@item @code{bmkx-auto-light-when-jump}---highlight automatically when
you jump.
@end itemize

Both options accept the values: @code{autonamed-bookmark},
@code{non-autonamed-bookmark}, @code{any-bookmark},
@code{autonamed-in-buffer}, @code{non-autonamed-in-buffer},
@code{all-in-buffer}, @code{nil} (off).

@section Pulse Highlight on Jump
@vindex bmkx-highlight-on-jump-flag

If @code{bmkx-highlight-on-jump-flag} is non-nil (the default), jumping
to a bookmark that has no region briefly pulse-highlights the landing
line via the built-in @file{pulse.el}.


@node Live Preview
@chapter Live Preview
@cindex preview
@cindex live preview

Live preview shows the bookmark's destination without committing to a
jump.  Two surfaces are provided.

@section In @file{*Bmkx List*}: @code{bmkx-list-preview-mode}
@cindex preview mode
@findex bmkx-list-preview-mode

A buffer-local minor mode in @file{*Bmkx List*}, modeled on the
built-in @code{next-error-follow-minor-mode}.  Toggle with @kbd{M-p}.

When the mode is enabled:

@itemize
@item Moving point onto a bookmark line opens its destination in
another window, without changing the selected window.
@item The mode-line lighter is @samp{ Pv}.
@item The window configuration is captured on mode-entry and restored
on mode-exit.
@end itemize

@vindex bmkx-list-preview-display-action
The display action used to show the destination is governed by
@code{bmkx-list-preview-display-action} (default: some other window,
@code{inhibit-same-window}).

@section On Demand: @kbd{C-o} and @key{TAB}
@findex bmkx-list-switch-other-window

In @file{*Bmkx List*}, @kbd{C-o} and @key{TAB} both invoke
@code{bmkx-list-switch-other-window}: open the bookmark in another
window, leaving the cursor in the list buffer.  Useful for one-off
peeking without entering the full preview mode.

@section In the Minibuffer: consult Integration
@cindex consult integration
@vindex bmkx-preview-use-consult-flag

When the @code{consult} package is loaded and
@code{bmkx-preview-use-consult-flag} is non-nil (the default), the
interactive bookmark-name read for @code{bmkx-jump} (and its
other-window and other-frame variants) is routed through
@code{consult--read} with @code{consult--bookmark-preview} as the
@code{:state} callback---the same mechanism @code{consult-bookmark}
uses.  You get live preview as you move through completion candidates.

If @code{consult} is not loaded, the read falls back to plain
@code{bmkx-completing-read}---no behavior change.


@node Casual Integration
@chapter Casual Integration
@cindex Casual
@cindex Transient menu

The optional file @file{casual-bmkx.el} provides a discoverable
Transient-based menu UI for @file{*Bmkx List*}, in the style of the
@uref{https://github.com/kickingvegas/casual, Casual suite}.

@section Activation

Requires the @code{casual-lib} package (from MELPA, part of the Casual
suite).  When @code{casual-lib} is installed, @file{casual-bmkx.el} is
loaded automatically and binds:

@table @kbd
@item c
@code{casual-bmkx-tmenu}---in @code{bmkx-list-mode-map}.  Opens the
Casual menu.
@end table

(Casual's own ecosystem uses @kbd{C-o} as the entry-point key, but in
@code{bmkx-list-mode} that is already taken by
@code{bmkx-list-switch-other-window}.  @kbd{c} was free.)

If @code{casual-lib} is not installed, Bookmark-X runs unchanged and
@kbd{c} is unbound.

@section Menu Layout

The main menu groups commands by intent: Move, Mark, Delete, Filter and
Show, Edit, Files, Preview, Sort (own submenu), Help, Quit.  See the
in-Emacs help (@kbd{?} in the transient) for the live list.


@node Cycling
@chapter Cycling: the Navigation List
@cindex cycling
@cindex navigation list
@cindex navlist

Bookmark-X lets you @emph{cycle} through a set of bookmarks---like
``favorites'' buttons on a TV remote.  The set being cycled is the
@dfn{navigation list} (navlist).

@section Defining the Navlist

@table @code
@item bmkx-choose-navlist-of-type
@kbd{C-x x :}---all bookmarks of a given type.
@item bmkx-choose-navlist-from-bookmark-list
@kbd{C-x x B}---bookmarks corresponding to a bookmark-list bookmark, or
the current @file{*Bmkx List*} state.
@end table

If you do not define one, the first cycling key takes a snapshot of
the current bookmarks (or of bookmarks for the current file/buffer, for
the file/buffer-specific cycling keys).

@section Cycling Commands

@multitable @columnfractions .42 .28 .28
@headitem Command @tab Forward key @tab Backward key
@item @code{bmkx-next-bookmark-repeat}                     @tab @kbd{C-x x f} / @kbd{C-x x C-f} / @kbd{C-x x @key{right}} @tab @kbd{C-x x b} / @kbd{C-x x C-b} / @kbd{C-x x @key{left}}
@item @code{bmkx-next-bookmark-this-file/buffer-repeat}    @tab @kbd{C-x x n} / @kbd{C-x x C-n} / @kbd{C-x x @key{down}}  @tab @kbd{C-x x p} / @kbd{C-x x C-p} / @kbd{C-x x @key{up}}
@item @code{bmkx-next-lighted-this-buffer-repeat}          @tab @kbd{C-x x C-@key{down}} @tab @kbd{C-x x C-@key{up}}
@end multitable

After @kbd{C-x x} you can also rotate the mouse wheel to cycle.

Show @file{*Bmkx List*} filtered to the navigation list with
@code{bmkx-navlist-bmenu-list} (@kbd{C-x x N}).


@node Automatic Bookmarking
@chapter Automatic Bookmarking
@cindex automatic bookmarking

@section On a Hook

Add @code{bmkx-set-automatic-bookmark} to any hook to create a bookmark
whenever that hook runs:

@lisp
(add-hook 'imenu-after-jump-hook #'bmkx-set-automatic-bookmark)
@end lisp

The bookmark created is an autonamed bookmark.

@section Idle-Period Bookmarking
@findex bmkx-automatic-bookmark-mode

@code{bmkx-automatic-bookmark-mode} is a buffer-local minor mode that
sets an autonamed bookmark whenever Emacs has been idle for
@code{bmkx-automatic-bookmark-mode-delay} seconds in the current
buffer.  @code{bmkx-global-automatic-bookmark-mode} turns it on
everywhere (a bookmark is still only created for the currently selected
buffer).

Tuning options:

@itemize
@item @code{bmkx-automatic-bookmark-mode-lighter}---mode-line lighter
(default @samp{Auto-Bmk}; set to @code{""} to hide).
@item @code{bmkx-automatic-bookmark-min-distance}---minimum distance
(in characters) from the nearest existing automatic bookmark.
@item @code{bmkx-automatic-bookmark-set-function}---which command to
use.
@end itemize

@section Automatic Info Bookmarking
@findex bmkx-info-auto-bookmark-mode

Enable @code{bmkx-info-auto-bookmark-mode} and every Info node you
visit either creates or updates a bookmark named @samp{(MANUAL) NODE}.
@code{bmkx-info-auto-type} chooses between @code{update-only} (default)
and @code{create-or-replace}; @code{bmkx-toggle-info-auto-type} flips
it.

The result is a persistent log of ``what I have read recently in the
Elisp / Emacs / @dots{} manuals.''


@node Autonamed Bookmarks
@chapter Autonamed Bookmarks
@cindex autonamed bookmarks

An @dfn{autonamed} bookmark is a regular, persistent bookmark whose
name is generated automatically from a buffer name plus position
(default format: @samp{000058356 foo.el}---nine-digit position then
buffer name).  It records no region, only a position.

@table @code
@item bmkx-toggle-autonamed-bookmark-set/delete
@kbd{C-x x @key{RET}}.  Toggles the autonamed bookmark at point.
Setting one is one keystroke; deleting it is the same keystroke.  With
a prefix argument it deletes @emph{all} autonamed bookmarks in the
current buffer (after confirmation).
@item bmkx-delete-bookmarks
@kbd{C-x x @key{delete}}.  Deletes individual bookmarks under cursor or
all bookmarks in the buffer (any type).
@end table

Other autonamed commands (not bound by default):
@code{bmkx-set-autonamed-bookmark-at-line},
@code{bmkx-set-autonamed-regexp-buffer},
@code{bmkx-set-autonamed-regexp-region},
@code{bmkx-occur-create-autonamed-bookmarks}.

If you do not want autonamed bookmarks to persist across sessions:

@lisp
(add-hook 'kill-buffer-hook 'bmkx-delete-autonamed-this-buffer-no-confirm)
(add-hook 'kill-emacs-hook  'bmkx-delete-autonamed-no-confirm)
@end lisp

Alternative: make autonamed bookmarks @emph{temporary} via
@code{bmkx-autotemp-bookmark-predicates} (the default), and they will
not be saved.  @xref{Temporary Bookmarks}.

Customize the name format with @code{bmkx-autoname-format} and
@code{bmkx-autoname-bookmark-function}.  The special spec @samp{%B}
refers to the buffer name within the format.


@node Temporary Bookmarks
@chapter Temporary Bookmarks
@cindex temporary bookmarks

A @dfn{temporary} bookmark is one that will not be written to the
bookmark file.  It exists only for the current session.

@section Temporary-Bookmarking Mode
@findex bmkx-temporary-bookmarking-mode

@code{bmkx-temporary-bookmarking-mode} (@kbd{M-L} in @file{*Bmkx List*})
turns on a minor mode that:

@enumerate
@item Switches to an empty bookmark file.
@item Turns off auto-saving (@code{bookmark-save-flag}).
@end enumerate

Every bookmark you create in this mode is therefore session-local.
The mode-line indicator changes to @samp{TEMPORARY Bookmarking}.

@section Per-Bookmark Temporary Flag

@multitable @columnfractions .47 .18 .35
@headitem Command @tab Key @tab Meaning
@item @code{bmkx-toggle-temporary-bookmark}                @tab @kbd{C-M-X} @tab Toggle for this line's bookmark.
@item @code{bmkx-bmenu-toggle-marked-temporary/savable}    @tab @kbd{M-X}   @tab Toggle for the marked bookmarks.
@item Temporary mark/show commands                          @tab @kbd{X M} / @kbd{X S} @tab Mark / show only temporary.
@item @code{bmkx-toggle-autotemp-on-set}                   @tab @kbd{C-x x x} @tab Toggle: make every new bookmark temporary.
@end multitable

@section Autotemp Predicates
@vindex bmkx-autotemp-bookmark-predicates

@code{bmkx-autotemp-bookmark-predicates} is a list of predicates---
typically type predicates such as @code{bmkx-autonamed-bookmark-p}---
that decide which bookmarks become temporary automatically when created
or updated.  The default makes autonamed bookmarks temporary.

@code{bmkx-delete-all-temporary-bookmarks} removes them all from the
current list at once.

Temporary bookmarks are flagged with @kbd{X} in @file{*Bmkx List*}.


@node Bookmark Records
@chapter Bookmark Records
@cindex bookmark record format
@cindex bookmark-alist

A bookmark is a list whose @code{car} is its name (a string) and whose
@code{cdr} is a @dfn{property alist}.  A typical record:

@example
("README"
 (id          . "8f3a7b3c-4dd5-...")
 (filename    . "/home/me/proj/README")
 (front-context-string . "## Introduction")
 (rear-context-string  . "")
 (position    . 1234)
 (last-modified 26013 12345 0 0)
 (visits      . 7)
 (tags ("doc") ("project" . "myproj")))
@end example

@cindex @code{id} property

Every record carries an @code{(id . STRING)} property.  The id is
opaque (@code{format-time-string} plus random hex bits), assigned at
record creation by @code{bookmark-make-record-default}.  Records read
from a file that lack an @code{id} (created by the built-in or by older
Bookmark-X versions) get one generated at load time and the alist is
marked dirty so the next save writes them.

@xref{Migration}, for why the @code{id} field exists and how it relates
to bookmark identity.

@section Lookup Helpers

@table @code
@item bmkx-get-bookmark
@code{(assoc NAME bookmark-alist)}.  Names are unique.
@item bmkx-get-by-id
Find a record by id.  Useful when a bookmark name may have changed.
@end table

@section Name Uniqueness
@cindex name uniqueness

Bookmark names are enforced unique within @code{bookmark-alist}.  Two
mechanisms maintain this:

@itemize
@item @strong{Auto-disambiguation on creation.}  When
@code{bookmark-store} is asked to create a new bookmark whose name
collides with an existing one, the new bookmark is auto-renamed
@samp{foo} @result{} @samp{foo<2>} @result{} @samp{foo<3>} @result{} @dots{}
@item @strong{Deduplication on load.}
@code{bmkx-deduplicate-bookmark-names} runs on
@code{bmkx-read-bookmark-file-hook} and renames any duplicate names
found in a loaded bookmark file.
@end itemize

@section Reading and Writing Bookmark Files
@cindex bookmark file, format

Bookmark files written by this fork are plain printable Lisp.  No
@code{print-circle} markers, no shared structure: just the bookmark
alist as a single readable form.

The format is identical to what built-in @file{bookmark.el} writes,
with one extra alist entry per record:

@example
(id . "20260601T144831-3f5a7c")
@end example

The built-in ignores this entry on read and preserves it on write.

@anchor{Round Trip Caveat}
@subsection Caveat: the Built-in Strips Metadata on Re-Set
@cindex round-trip
@cindex metadata loss
@cindex interop warning

The interop is safe @emph{as long as the built-in does not modify
the record}.  When the built-in only loads a file, displays it, and
saves it back, every alist entry that built-in @file{bookmark.el}
does not recognise is preserved verbatim --- including the
@code{id}, tags, annotation, visit count, last-access time, lighting
override, and any other Bookmark-X property.

However, the built-in's @code{bookmark-set} (and the commands that
call it, including @kbd{C-x r m}) does not @emph{update} an existing
record: it @emph{rebuilds} it from scratch using
@code{bookmark-make-record-default}.  Built-in
@code{bookmark-make-record-default} only knows about the standard
@file{bookmark.el} properties.  The result: if you have a bookmark
named @samp{notes} carrying Bookmark-X metadata (tags,
@code{annotation}, @code{id}, etc.) and you re-set it from a vanilla
Emacs session via @kbd{C-x r m notes RET}, the new record overwrites
the old, and all of those properties are gone.  When the file is
saved next, the metadata is lost on disk too.

To avoid this:

@itemize
@item
If you have to edit a Bookmark-X file from a vanilla Emacs session,
treat it as read-only --- jump to bookmarks, but do not @kbd{C-x r m}
to update one in place.
@item
If you regularly use both vanilla Emacs and Bookmark-X on the same
machine, keep them on @emph{different} bookmark files.
@xref{Multiple Bookmark Files}, for how to switch.
@item
If you accidentally re-set a bookmark from a vanilla session, you
can recover from a backup written by Bookmark-X (set
@code{bookmark-version-control} to @code{t}; backups are kept next
to the bookmark file as @samp{~/.emacs.bmk.~1~} etc.).
@end itemize

@xref{Migration}, for the rationale behind the @code{id} field and
the file-format simplification.


@node Customization
@chapter Customization
@cindex customization

Run @kbd{M-x customize-group RET bookmark-plus RET} for the full
customize interface.  This section enumerates the most commonly tweaked
options.  Many more are listed in @code{customize-group}.

@section Bookmark Naming and Properties

@vtable @code
@item bmkx-new-bookmark-default-names
List of functions consulted to generate the default name for a new
bookmark.
@item bmkx-properties-to-keep
Properties preserved when you overwrite a bookmark.  Default:
@code{(tags annotation)}.
@item bmkx-count-multi-mods-as-one-flag
If non-nil (default), count all the modifications a single command
makes as one for @code{bookmark-save-flag} purposes.
@item bmkx-save-new-location-flag
