@node Migration
@chapter Migration from Upstream Bookmark-X
@cindex migration
@cindex differences from upstream

This is a fork of Drew Adams' Bookmark-X, modernized for Emacs 30+.  If
you are coming from the original, here is what changed.

@section Sibling, Not Replacement
@cindex sibling design

Upstream Bookmark-X @emph{replaced} many built-in @file{bookmark.el}
functions in place: @code{bookmark-set}, @code{bookmark-store},
@code{bookmark-get-bookmark}, the bmenu rendering, and more.  The
replacements were richer, but they also tightly coupled Bookmark-X to
every change in the built-in.

This fork is an @strong{additive sibling}.  No built-in function is
redefined.  Every command lives under the @code{bmkx-} prefix.  Both
systems coexist and operate on the same @code{bookmark-alist} and the
same on-disk bookmark file; you can call either at any time.

The architectural change that made this possible is the new
@code{id} field, described next.


@section The @code{id} Field: Identity in This Fork
@cindex @code{id} field
@cindex bookmark identity
@cindex @code{bmkx-full-record} (upstream)

The single most important difference between this fork and upstream
Bookmark-X is how bookmarks are identified internally.  Understanding
this matters if you write Emacs Lisp that manipulates bookmarks; it
matters less for interactive use.

@subsection What Upstream Did

The user-visible effect upstream achieved was simple: @strong{two
bookmarks could have the exact same display name}.  This was useful
for the @dfn{autofile} pattern --- creating bookmarks named after
files (e.g.@: many @samp{README.md} files, one per project), all
sharing the same short name.

Internally, upstream got this by attaching a hidden tag to each
bookmark's name string.  Even though two name strings displayed as
the same text, they carried different hidden tags pointing to
different records, so the code could still tell them apart.  Emacs
calls these hidden tags @dfn{text properties} on strings; the
specific tag was called @code{bmkx-full-record}.

The same hidden-tag trick also bought upstream three pieces of
internal speed and convenience that did not affect what the user
saw, but mattered to the implementation:

@enumerate
@item
Going from a name to its record was a single hidden-tag read
instead of a search through the bookmark list.
@item
Programs holding an old name string still worked after the bookmark
was renamed in the list --- the hidden tag still pointed at the
same record.
@item
Each row in @file{*Bmkx List*} carried its own record in the hidden
tag of the displayed name, so the bmenu code didn't need to look up
the name to find the record.
@end enumerate

The cost was paid in the on-disk file format.  Hidden tags on
shared strings can only be saved if Emacs is told to preserve
shared-structure (@code{print-circle}); the resulting bookmark file
contained markers like @samp{#1=#1#}.  Files written this way could
not be safely read and re-written by Emacs's built-in
@file{bookmark.el}, which does not turn on shared-structure
preservation when it writes.

@subsection What This Fork Does

Every bookmark record carries an opaque @code{(id . STRING)}
property:

@example
("README.md"
 (id . "20260601T144831-3f5a7c")
 (filename . "/home/me/proj/README.md")
 (position . 1234)
 @dots{})
@end example

The id is generated by @code{bookmark-make-record-default} at record
creation time.  It uses @code{format-time-string} plus a few random
hex bits, giving an opaque, sortable, collision-resistant key.
Records read from a file that lack an id (written by built-in
@file{bookmark.el} or older Bookmark-X) have one generated at load
time, and the alist is marked dirty so the next save persists them.

Names are now enforced unique within @code{bookmark-alist} by
auto-disambiguation: if @code{bmkx-store} is asked to create a new
bookmark whose name collides with an existing one, the new bookmark
is renamed @samp{foo} @result{} @samp{foo<2>} @result{}
@samp{foo<3>} @result{} @dots{} before being added.  Files written
by older versions with duplicate names are deduplicated on load by
@code{bmkx-deduplicate-bookmark-names}.

@subsection What Changed in Practice

Compared with upstream:

@multitable @columnfractions .45 .55
@headitem Capability @tab This fork
@item Display-identical duplicate names           @tab Auto-disambiguated as @samp{foo}, @samp{foo<2>}, @dots{}
@item Looking up a record from its name           @tab Search through the list (was a constant-time tag read)
@item Programs holding a name across a rename     @tab Should hold the @code{id} instead (see Practical Guidance)
@item Each @file{*Bmkx List*} row as its own record handle @tab Read the line, then look up the name
@end multitable

The first row is the only user-visible change.  An autofile use case
(many @samp{README.md} in different directories) that previously
showed two identical-looking rows now shows @samp{README.md} and
@samp{README.md<2>}.  The behavior is the same; the visual is
different.

The other three rows are invisible to interactive users.
Programmatic callers may need adjustment --- see Practical Guidance
below.

@subsection What This Fork Gained

@itemize
@item
@strong{Plain printable file format.}  No @code{print-circle}
markers, no shared-structure tricks.  Bookmark files are valid input
to @code{read} under any settings.  About 300--400 lines of property
machinery, file-write gymnastics, and ``maybe-unpropertize''
helpers were deleted from the source.
@item
@strong{Interop with the built-in.}  A file written by this fork is
read by built-in @file{bookmark.el}; a file written by the built-in
is read by this fork (and the @code{bmkx-read-bookmark-file-hook}
backfills any missing @code{id} fields at load time).  Records the
built-in does not modify are written back unchanged.  See @ref{Round
Trip Caveat}, for the one important caveat when the built-in
@emph{modifies} a record.
@item
@strong{The sibling architecture itself.}  Without giving up the
hidden-tag trick, this fork could not stop redefining
@code{bookmark-store}, @code{bookmark-get-bookmark}, and friends.
The id field made the sibling design possible.
@item
@strong{Identity that survives rename.}  The id lives in the
record, so renaming a bookmark in place preserves the id.  Sequence
bookmarks and bookmark-list bookmarks can safely reference their
components by id rather than by name.
@end itemize

@subsection Practical Guidance for Lisp Callers

If you write Emacs Lisp that holds a reference to a bookmark across
edits, renames, file reloads, or sessions: @strong{hold the id, not
the name}.  The name is a display label and may change at any time;
the id is stable.

@example
;; Save:
(let ((id (bookmark-prop-get "my-bookmark" 'id)))
  ;; @dots{} stash id somewhere @dots{}
  )

;; Retrieve later, even if "my-bookmark" was renamed:
(let ((rec (bmkx-get-by-id stored-id)))
  (when rec
    (bmkx-jump (bookmark-name-from-full-record rec))))
@end example

For ad-hoc interactive use the name is fine; the rename window is
small and the consequences of staleness are usually just a
@samp{No such bookmark} error.

@section No Compatibility Aliases
@cindex no compat aliases

Where this fork renamed an upstream symbol (for example, the bmenu
buffer became @file{*Bmkx List*} and many @code{bookmark-bmenu-*}
defuns became @code{bmkx-list-*}), no compatibility alias was kept.
The user-visible Bookmark-X commands are all @code{bmkx-*}; the
built-in @code{bookmark-*} names always refer to the built-in.

If you had user code that called @code{bookmark-bmenu-foo}, point it at
the corresponding @code{bmkx-list-foo} or @code{bmkx-bmenu-foo}.

@section Emacs 30 or Newer Required
@cindex Emacs 30 requirement

Loading the package on Emacs @math{<} 30 signals an error at load time.
Many polyfills for older Emacs (cl-puthash dispatch, find-tag-default
fallbacks, Emacs-21 fringe-style guards, @dots{}) have been deleted.

@section Dropped External Dependencies
@cindex dropped dependencies

Replaced with built-in equivalents:

@multitable @columnfractions .35 .65
@headitem Upstream dep @tab Replacement
@item @file{crosshairs.el}       @tab Built-in @file{pulse.el}.
@item @file{fit-frame.el}        @tab Built-in @code{fit-frame-to-buffer}.
@item @file{narrow-indirect.el}  @tab Built-in @code{clone-indirect-buffer-other-window} + @code{narrow-to-region}.
@item @file{thingatpt+.el}       @tab Inlined as @code{bmkx-symbol-nearest-point} and friends.
@item @file{zones.el} helper calls @tab Inlined as @code{bmkx-read-any-variable}, @code{bmkx-readable-marker} (the izones bookmark type is still gated on @file{zones.el}).
@item @file{linkd.el} (dead since 2007) @tab Built-in @code{outline-minor-mode}.
@item Active @file{emacs-w3m} integration @tab @code{bmkx-jump-w3m} routes to @code{bmkx-jump-eww}; no new W3M bookmarks created.
@item Icicles completion-framework integration @tab Plain @code{completing-read}; layer @code{vertico} / @code{consult} / @code{marginalia} on top.
@end multitable

@file{dired+.el} is still recognised as an optional dependency.

@section File Format
@cindex file format

Bookmark files are now plain printable Lisp---no
@code{print-circle}/@code{#1=#1#} markers, no @code{bmkx-full-record}
text property on names.  Files round-trip through built-in
@file{bookmark.el} losslessly.

@section New Capabilities
@cindex new capabilities

@itemize
@item Live preview in @file{*Bmkx List*} via @code{bmkx-list-preview-mode}
(@xref{Live Preview}).
@item @code{consult} integration for @code{bmkx-jump} (same chapter).
@item Optional Casual-style Transient menu via @file{casual-bmkx.el}
(@xref{Casual Integration}).
@item Stable bookmark identity via the @code{id} record property.
@item Hard Emacs-30 gate, much cleaner source (~600 lines of dead
version-gates and polyfills removed).
@end itemize


